article.description:
Boris Diaw scored 25 points in his first game in
Atlanta since he was traded, leading the Suns to a 110-106 win over the Hawks on Friday night.
article.headline: Diaw scores 25 in return to Atlanta as Suns win
article.linkText: Diaw scores 25 in return to Atlanta as Suns win
article.story:
ATLANTA (AP) -- Boris Diaw insisted he wasn't trying to prove a point in his first game back in Atlanta since he was traded to Phoenix. It sure looked that way to everyone else. Diaw scored 25 points and Steve Nash hit a go-ahead 3-pointer with 35 seconds left, leading the Suns to a 110-106 win over the Hawks on Friday night. Diaw, who was a forgotten backup for Atlanta before he was traded to the Suns last summer, added eight rebounds and five assists. "He came in here and kicked our behinds tonight," Atlanta forward Al Harrington said. "I know the game meant a lot to him, and he played that way." Diaw, a 2003 first-round pick for the Hawks, said it wasn't a statement game, but even his new coach saw it differently. "I don't know if it's anything personal," Suns coach Mike D'Antoni said. "You'd have to ask him. But it sure seemed like it." Joe Johnson, who came to Atlanta in the trade, led the Hawks with 27 points, seven rebounds and five assists. "It was personal for both of them," Harrington said. "They both did a great job tonight." The Hawks pulled even at 102-all on a jumper by Tyronn Lue with 1:34 left, but a basket by Diaw gave the lead back to the Suns. Lue and Nash traded 3-pointers, leaving the Suns with a 107-105 advantage with 35 seconds left. After a free throw by Harrington cut the lead to one point, Atlanta's Josh Childress was called for goaltending on Leandro Barbosa, leaving the Suns with a 109-106 lead with 19 seconds left. Nash had 22 points and nine assists for Phoenix. Shawn Marion had 15 points and Barbosa added 14. Lue scored 17 points and Harrington added 16 for the Hawks, who have lost eight of 10. Diaw spent much of the 2004-05 season as the last man on Hawks coach Mike Woodson's bench. Though he did not miss a game due to injury, illness or suspension, Diaw was held out of 16 games by Woodson and averaged only 4.8 points. "He felt like he was held back here," Atlanta's Josh Smith said. "He had an opportunity in Phoenix, and he's playing to his potential now." Most Hawks fans didn't mind when Diaw was sent to the Suns with two conditional first-round picks in the Aug. 19 trade for Johnson. But with Phoenix, Diaw has started 32 games. Diaw is on the verge of joining LeBron James, Dwyane Wade and Jason Kidd as the only NBA players to average at least six rebounds and six assists. He returned to Atlanta averaging 11.6 points, 6.4 rebounds and 5.9 assists. "It's pretty much the way I've been used," Diaw said. "I know, for example, Mike D'Antoni has been playing in Europe and coaching in Europe. I'm a kind of European player. You've got to use me the right way." Johnson, averaging 19.1 points to lead Atlanta, had 11 points as the Hawks led 31-22 after the first quarter. The Suns led 57-50 at halftime. Johnson had eight points in the final 2:30 of the third period to help the Hawks tie it at 80 entering the final period. Salim Stoudamire's 3-pointer with 5:08 left gave the Hawks a 98-96 lead, but Nash quickly answered to tie it.

Game notes
Former baseball star Cal Ripken Jr., in Atlanta to conduct a baseball clinic at Georgia Tech Saturday, attended the game. ... Nikoloz Tskitishvili, the 7-footer acquired by Phoenix from Minnesota on Thursday for a 2006 second-round draft pick, was not active for the game. ... The Hawks made 16 of 17 free throws. The only miss was Harrington's second attempt with 23 seconds left. ... The Suns, who won at Miami on Thursday night, have won consecutive road games for the first time since Dec. 26-31, when they won four straight on the road.
